---
description: AI agents, chatbot, and agent copilot rules
globs: ai/**, agents/**, tools/**, workflows/**, orchestration/**
---

Product context:
- GenAI + RAG chatbot for customer queries; agent copilot for suggested replies, KB retrieval, ticket summary, troubleshooting steps, conversation drafting, one-click response generation.
- NLP intelligence: intent detection, sentiment, urgency, topic clustering, complaint/escalation detection, language detection.
- Tools may include: KB search, ticket lookup, customer context, CRM, external APIs; all behind validated tool layer.

Agent system architecture:
- Separate planner, executor, tools, memory, state, and evaluation logic.
- Agents must be modular and role-specific (customer-facing chatbot vs agent copilot).
- Tool calls must be explicit, validated, and logged.

Agent rules:
- Agents must not directly access databases or external APIs except through a defined tool layer.
- Prompts must be templated and stored separately from orchestration logic.
- Keep critical business workflows (routing, escalation, SLA) deterministic where possible.
- Add output validation and fallback behavior; use structured schemas for agent outputs in production.
- Prefer supervisor/policy logic for multi-agent coordination when needed.
- Support auto-generated responses and AI suggestions for human agents per PRD.

Tooling rules:
- Every tool must have: clear purpose, input schema, output schema, failure behavior.
- Tools must be side-effect aware; sensitive tools must enforce auth and authorization.
- Validate tool inputs and outputs; restrict tool access by policy (security rule).

Memory/state rules:
- Separate short-term conversational state from long-term memory.
- Store long-term memory only when product requirements justify it; track provenance when relevant.
- Unified conversation thread and history sync across channels (see omni-channel rule).

Do not:
- Let agents perform unrestricted actions.
- Hide tool errors.
- Mix prompt text deeply into service/business code.